Chapter 2: Mathematical Preliminaries

2.1 Information Geometry

Let \mathcal{P}(X) denote the space of probability measures on a sample space X. A statistical model is a parametrized family \{p_\theta \mid \theta \in \Theta\} where \Theta \subseteq \mathbb{R}^n is open. Under regularity conditions, \Theta carries a natural Riemannian metric: the Fisher information metric

g_{ij}(\theta) = \mathbb{E}_{p_\theta}\!\left[ \partial_i \log p_\theta \, \partial_j \log p_\theta \right] = \int p_\theta(x) \frac{\partial \log p_\theta(x)}{\partial \theta^i} \frac{\partial \log p_\theta(x)}{\partial \theta^j} dx.

For exponential families p_\theta(x) = \exp(\theta \cdot T(x) - \psi(\theta)) h(x), the Fisher metric is the Hessian of the log partition function:

g_{ij}(\theta) = \partial_i \partial_j \psi(\theta).

The Kullback-Leibler divergence D_{KL}(p \parallel q) = \int p(x) \log \frac{p(x)}{q(x)} dx generates both the metric and a dual pair of affine connections (\nabla, \nabla^*) that make (\Theta, g, \nabla, \nabla^*) a dually flat space (Amari, 1985). In dually flat spaces, geodesics are straight lines in natural or expectation parameters, and the divergence satisfies a generalized Pythagorean theorem.

Shannon entropy H(p) = -\mathbb{E}_p[\log p] serves as our regularization functional. For exponential families, a key computation gives:

\operatorname{grad}_g H = -\theta

in natural parameters. Indeed, from \partial_j H = -\theta^k g_{jk} we have (\operatorname{grad}_g H)^i = g^{ij} \partial_j H = -\theta^i.

Proposition 2.1 (Strong convexity of regularized loss). For an exponential family in natural parameters, the negative entropy -H is 1‑strongly geodesically convex with respect to the Fisher metric. Consequently, for any \lambda > 0, the regularized loss \mathcal{L}_\lambda = \mathcal{L}_{\text{task}} - \lambda H is \lambda-strongly geodesically convex if \mathcal{L}_{\text{task}} is geodesically convex.

Proof. In natural parameters, the Fisher metric is constant: g_{ij} = \partial_i \partial_j \psi(\theta). The Hessian of -H with respect to the Levi-Civita connection of g is the identity matrix (Amari, 1998). This can be seen by noting that in the expectation parameters \eta, the metric becomes Euclidean and -H is a quadratic function. Hence \nabla_g^2 (-\lambda H) = \lambda I. Adding a convex function preserves strong convexity with at least the same modulus. ∎

2.2 Categorical Fisher Information

Following Bonnasse-Gahot and Nadal , for a classification task with categories y \in \mathcal{Y}, the categorical Fisher information is:

J_{\text{cat}}(\theta) = \mathbb{E}_{p(y|x)} \left[ \nabla_\theta \log p(y|x) \nabla_\theta \log p(y|x)^\top \right].

Their key result: minimizing the Bayes cost (cross-entropy loss) implies maximizing the mutual information between categories and neural activities, which in turn forces the neural Fisher information g_{\text{neural}} to align with J_{\text{cat}}. Mathematically, optimal learning achieves:

g_{\text{neural}}(\theta) \approx J_{\text{cat}}(\theta)

up to scaling and within the relevant subspace . This alignment induces expansion of neural space near decision boundaries—a phenomenon they term categorical perception.

2.3 Category Theory

A category \mathbf{C} consists of objects \text{Ob}(\mathbf{C}) and morphisms \text{Hom}_{\mathbf{C}}(A,B) for each pair A,B, with composition \circ and identities \text{id}_A. A functor F: \mathbf{C} \to \mathbf{D} maps objects to objects and morphisms to morphisms preserving composition and identities. A natural transformation \alpha: F \Rightarrow G is a family of morphisms \alpha_A: F(A) \to G(A) in \mathbf{D} such that for any f: A \to B in \mathbf{C}, \alpha_B \circ F(f) = G(f) \circ \alpha_A.

A monad on \mathbf{C} is a triple (T, \eta, \mu) with T: \mathbf{C} \to \mathbf{C} an endofunctor, \eta: \text{Id}_{\mathbf{C}} \Rightarrow T (unit) and \mu: T^2 \Rightarrow T (multiplication) satisfying the monad laws. The Kleisli category \mathbf{C}_T has the same objects as \mathbf{C}, but morphisms A \to B are morphisms A \to T(B) in \mathbf{C}. Composition is Kleisli composition: g \circ_T f = \mu_Z \circ T(g) \circ f.

2.4 Gradient Flows and Geodesic Convexity

On a Riemannian manifold (M,g), the gradient flow of a smooth function \mathcal{L}: M \to \mathbb{R} is the curve \theta(t) satisfying

\dot{\theta}(t) = -\operatorname{grad}_g \mathcal{L}(\theta(t)),

where \operatorname{grad}_g \mathcal{L} is the unique vector field with g(\operatorname{grad}_g \mathcal{L}, X) = d\mathcal{L}(X) for all X. In coordinates, (\operatorname{grad}_g \mathcal{L})^i = g^{ij} \partial_j \mathcal{L}.

A function \mathcal{L} is geodesically convex if for any geodesic \gamma:[0,1]\to M,

\mathcal{L}(\gamma(t)) \le (1-t)\mathcal{L}(\gamma(0)) + t\mathcal{L}(\gamma(1)).

It is \mu-strongly geodesically convex if

\mathcal{L}(\gamma(t)) \le (1-t)\mathcal{L}(\gamma(0)) + t\mathcal{L}(\gamma(1)) - \frac{\mu}{2} t(1-t) d(\gamma(0),\gamma(1))^2.

For \mu-strongly convex functions on complete manifolds, gradient flows converge exponentially to the unique minimizer. The Polyak–Łojasiewicz inequality \|\operatorname{grad}_g \mathcal{L}\|^2_g \ge 2\mu (\mathcal{L} - \mathcal{L}^*) is sufficient for exponential convergence even without full convexity.

2.5 Ricci Curvature and Stability

The Ricci curvature \operatorname{Ric}(v,v) measures the average sectional curvature in directions containing v. A lower bound on Ricci curvature implies that geodesics tend to converge (positive Ricci) or diverge (negative Ricci). In control theory, Ricci curvature appears in comparison theorems that control the growth of Lyapunov functions along flows . For a \mu-strongly convex function V on a manifold with \operatorname{Ric} \ge \rho g, one can show (Bakry-Émery) that:

\frac{d}{dt} V(\gamma(t)) \le -\mu V(\gamma(t)) + \frac{L^2}{2} \|\dot\gamma\|^2 + \frac{|\rho|}{2} d(\gamma, \gamma^*)^2,

where the curvature term is positive if \rho is negative. This inequality underpins our composition theorem.

2.6 Cencov's Theorem and Stochastic Maps

Cencov's theorem (Čencov, 1982) states that the Fisher metric is the unique Riemannian metric (up to scaling) on the simplex of probability distributions that is invariant under congruent embeddings by Markov morphisms. A corollary: Markov kernels (stochastic maps) are contractions of the Fisher metric when the domain and codomain are equipped with the Fisher geometry. For any Markov kernel k: M \to N, the induced push-forward satisfies k_*^* g_N \preceq g_M. This provides a rigorous justification for information-contracting morphisms in our category.

2.7 The PDE Perspective on Transformers

Recent work by Zhang and Zhou  reconceptualizes Transformers as discretizations of a continuous spatiotemporal dynamical system governed by a master Partial Differential Equation:

\frac{\partial h}{\partial t} = \mathcal{F}(h, \nabla h, \nabla^2 h, \ldots)

where self-attention acts as a non-local interaction term, feed-forward networks as local reactions, and residual connections as the discretization scheme itself. Within this framework, depth becomes a continuous time parameter, and the discrete layer index l corresponds to time t = l \Delta t. This perspective reveals that standard residual connections implement a simple Euler discretization with fixed step size, while more sophisticated architectures can implement adaptive schemes.

2.8 Langevin Dynamics on Manifolds

For a manifold (M, g), the Langevin SDE is:

d\theta_t = -\text{grad}_g \mathcal{L}(\theta_t) dt + \sqrt{2\beta^{-1}} dW_t

where dW_t is the Brownian motion on M (generated by the Laplace-Beltrami operator \Delta_g). The generator is \mathcal{L} = \Delta_g - \nabla\mathcal{L} \cdot \nabla. Under a Ricci curvature bound \text{Ric} \ge \rho g, the Bakry-Émery criterion gives a log-Sobolev inequality, implying exponential convergence to the invariant measure \pi(\theta) \propto e^{-\beta \mathcal{L}(\theta)} with rate \alpha \ge \mu + \rho when \mathcal{L} is \mu-convex .

