Chapter 3: Axiomatic Framework

3.1 The Category Stat

Definition 3.1 (Statistical manifold). A statistical manifold is a triple (M, g, (\nabla, \nabla^*)) where:

· M is a smooth manifold of probability distributions (parametrized by an open set \Theta \subseteq \mathbb{R}^n).
· g is the Fisher-Rao metric.
· (\nabla, \nabla^*) are dual torsion-free connections making (M,g,\nabla,\nabla^*) a dually flat space.

Definition 3.2 (Morphisms in Stat). A morphism k: M \to N is a Markov kernel k: M \times \Sigma_N \to [0,1] such that the induced push-forward map k_*: \mathcal{P}(M) \to \mathcal{P}(N) satisfies the information contraction property:

k_*^* g_N \preceq g_M,

i.e., for all tangent vectors v \in T_m M,

g_N( (dk)_m v, (dk)_m v) \le g_M(v, v).

Composition is composition of Markov kernels (Chapman-Kolmogorov). Identities are Dirac kernels.

Remark. This definition relaxes isometry to contraction, aligning with the Data Processing Inequality and allowing realistic neural transformations .

3.2 The Intentional Monad T

Let (\mathcal{G}, *, e) be a Lie monoid equipped with a bi-invariant Fisher metric (so left and right translations are isometries). We interpret \mathcal{G} as the space of possible goals.

Definition 3.3 (Goal-augmented manifold). For an object M in Stat, define T_0(M) = M \times \mathcal{G} with the product Fisher metric g_{M\times\mathcal{G}} = g_M \oplus g_{\mathcal{G}} and the product dual connections. This is again a statistical manifold.

Definition 3.4 (Intentional monad). Define the intentional monad T on Stat as:

· Endofunctor: T(M) = M \times \mathcal{G}. For a morphism k: M \to N, define T(k): T(M) \to T(N) by T(k)(m, g) = (k(m), g).
· Unit: \eta_M: M \to T(M) is the embedding \eta_M(m) = (m, e).
· Multiplication: \mu_M: T(T(M)) = (M \times \mathcal{G}) \times \mathcal{G} \to M \times \mathcal{G} by \mu_M((m, g_1), g_2) = (m, g_1 * g_2).

One verifies the monad laws using the monoid axioms. This is the writer monad with values in \mathcal{G}.

Definition 3.5 (Intentional morphism). A Kleisli morphism f: M \to N in Stat_T is a morphism f: M \to T(N) in Stat. For endomorphisms (M = N), we call f \epsilon-intentional if for every m \in M,

d_M(m, \pi_M \circ f(m)) \le \epsilon,

where \pi_M: T(M) \to M is the projection onto the first factor. This measures the "cost" of injecting the goal.

3.3 Intentional Flows

Definition 3.6 (Regularized loss). For a task specified by a smooth cost function \mathcal{L}_{\text{task}}: M \to \mathbb{R} and a regularization parameter \lambda \ge 0, define the regularized loss

\mathcal{L}_{\lambda}(\theta) = \mathcal{L}_{\text{task}}(\theta) - \lambda H(\theta),

where H is Shannon entropy. (The sign choice: maximizing entropy encourages exploration; minimizing entropy encourages exploitation. We keep \lambda \ge 0 and allow both cases by interpreting the sign in context.)

Definition 3.7 (Intentional flow). An intentional process is a curve \theta(t) in M satisfying the gradient flow of \mathcal{L}_{\lambda} with respect to the Fisher metric:

\dot{\theta}(t) = -\operatorname{grad}_g \mathcal{L}_{\lambda}(\theta(t)).

In coordinates,

\dot{\theta}^i = -g^{ij}(\theta) \left( \partial_j \mathcal{L}_{\text{task}} - \lambda \partial_j H \right) = -g^{ij}(\theta) \partial_j \mathcal{L}_{\text{task}} + \lambda \theta^i,

using \operatorname{grad}_g H = -\theta.

Definition 3.8 (Stability). An intentional flow is stable if \mathcal{L}_{\lambda}(\theta(t)) is bounded below and non-increasing along trajectories. It is asymptotically stable if it converges to a fixed point \theta^* as t \to \infty.

3.4 Metric Alignment Entropy

Definition 3.9 (Metric alignment entropy). For a learned metric g and categorical Fisher information J_{\text{cat}}, define the alignment gap:

\Delta(g, J_{\text{cat}}) = D_{\text{BR}}(g \parallel J_{\text{cat}}) = \frac{1}{2} \left( \operatorname{tr}(g^{-1} J_{\text{cat}}) - \log \det(g^{-1} J_{\text{cat}}) - n \right),

where D_{\text{BR}} is the Bregman divergence on the manifold of positive definite matrices. This measures the information loss due to metric mismatch.

