Chapter 7: Stochastic Intentional Flows and Future Directions

7.1 Stochastic Extension

We extend the deterministic intentional flow to a Langevin SDE on (M, g):

d\theta_t = -\text{grad}_g \mathcal{L}_\lambda(\theta_t) dt + \sqrt{2\beta^{-1}} dW_t

where dW_t is the Brownian motion on M (generated by the Laplace-Beltrami operator). The invariant measure is the Gibbs distribution \pi(\theta) \propto e^{-\beta \mathcal{L}_\lambda(\theta)}.

Theorem 7.1 (Convergence to Gibbs measure). Assume \operatorname{Ric}_g \ge \rho g and \mathcal{L}_\lambda is \mu-strongly convex. Then the transition kernel P_t of the Langevin diffusion satisfies the log-Sobolev inequality with constant \alpha \ge \mu + \rho, and consequently

\chi^2(P_t f \parallel \pi) \le e^{-2\alpha t} \chi^2(f \parallel \pi)

for any function f with \int f d\pi = 0. In particular, the law of \theta_t converges exponentially to \pi in relative entropy.

Proof. The Bakry-Émery criterion states that if \operatorname{Ric} + \nabla^2 \mathcal{L}_\lambda \ge \alpha g, then the generator satisfies a curvature-dimension condition CD(\alpha, \infty), which implies a log-Sobolev inequality with constant \alpha. Here \nabla^2 \mathcal{L}_\lambda \ge \mu g and \operatorname{Ric} \ge \rho g, so \operatorname{Ric} + \nabla^2 \mathcal{L}_\lambda \ge (\mu + \rho) g. Thus \alpha = \mu + \rho. The exponential convergence in \chi^2 follows from standard theory . ∎

This provides the first formal guarantee that stochastic training (SGD) in AttnRes architectures still reaches the geometric optimum, with a rate governed by the curvature and convexity.

