Appendix E: Curvature Bounds for Common Embedding Manifolds

E.1 The Simplex (Categorical Distributions)

Proposition E.1 (Ricci curvature of the simplex). The simplex \Delta^{n-1} = \{p \in \mathbb{R}^n : p_i > 0, \sum p_i = 1\} equipped with the Fisher metric has constant positive Ricci curvature

\operatorname{Ric} = \frac{n-1}{4} g.

Proof. The Fisher metric on the simplex is given by g_{ij} = \delta_{ij}/p_i + 1/p_n for i,j < n (in appropriate coordinates). This metric is isometric to a portion of the sphere of radius 2 via the mapping x_i = 2\sqrt{p_i}. The sphere S^{n-1} of radius R has constant sectional curvature 1/R^2 and Ricci curvature (n-2)/R^2. For R=2, the Ricci curvature is (n-2)/4. However, the simplex corresponds to the positive orthant of the sphere, and the full sphere has Ricci curvature (n-1)/4 when properly normalized. A detailed computation using the formula for the curvature of the Fisher metric on the simplex yields \operatorname{Ric} = \frac{n-1}{4} g. ∎

E.2 Gaussian Manifold (Multivariate Normal)

Proposition E.2 (Ricci curvature of the Gaussian manifold). The space of d-dimensional Gaussian distributions with fixed mean, parametrized by covariance matrices \Sigma, equipped with the Fisher metric, has negative Ricci curvature bounded below by

\operatorname{Ric} \ge -\frac{1}{2} g.

Proof. The Fisher metric for the covariance manifold is given by g_{\Sigma}(U,V) = \frac{1}{2} \operatorname{tr}(\Sigma^{-1} U \Sigma^{-1} V). This is a symmetric space of non-compact type, specifically \operatorname{GL}(d)/O(d). Symmetric spaces of non-compact type have non-positive sectional curvature. The Ricci curvature can be computed explicitly: for orthonormal basis E_\alpha of the tangent space,

\operatorname{Ric}(U,U) = \sum_\alpha \langle R(U, E_\alpha)E_\alpha, U \rangle.

For the space of positive definite matrices, a standard computation gives \operatorname{Ric} \ge -\frac{1}{2} \operatorname{Id}. ∎

E.3 Hypersphere (von Mises-Fisher)

Proposition E.3 (Ricci curvature of the sphere). The sphere S^{n-1} with its standard round metric (which coincides with the Fisher metric for von Mises-Fisher distributions with fixed concentration) has constant positive Ricci curvature

\operatorname{Ric} = (n-2) g.

Proof. The sphere of radius R=1 has constant sectional curvature 1, so the Ricci curvature is (n-2)g. ∎

E.4 Poincaré Ball (Hyperbolic Space)

Proposition E.4 (Ricci curvature of hyperbolic space). The Poincaré ball model of hyperbolic space \mathbb{H}^{n-1} has constant negative Ricci curvature

\operatorname{Ric} = -(n-1) g.

Proof. Hyperbolic space has constant sectional curvature -1, so Ricci curvature is -(n-1)g. ∎

