Appendix F: Diagonal-Plus-Low-Rank (DPLR) Analysis for Kimi Delta Attention

F.1 Kimi Delta Attention Update Rule

Following , the Kimi Delta Attention (KDA) update is given by:

S_t = \Lambda_t S_{t-1} + U_t V_t^\top,

where:

· S_t \in \mathbb{R}^{d_k \times d_v} is the state matrix at time t
· \Lambda_t = \operatorname{Diag}(\alpha_t) \in \mathbb{R}^{d_k \times d_k} is a diagonal matrix of channel-wise decay factors
· U_t \in \mathbb{R}^{d_k \times r}, V_t \in \mathbb{R}^{d_v \times r} are low-rank matrices with rank r \ll d_k, d_v

F.2 Metric Evolution

Proposition F.1 (Metric update). Let g_t be the Fisher information metric of the state S_t. Under the KDA update,

g_{t} = (\Lambda_t \otimes I) g_{t-1} (\Lambda_t \otimes I)^\top + \text{low-rank terms},

where \otimes denotes the Kronecker product.

Proof. The state S_t is obtained by a linear transformation of S_{t-1} plus a low-rank term. The Fisher information transforms according to the Jacobian of this transformation. The Jacobian with respect to S_{t-1} is \Lambda_t \otimes I (vectorizing S_t). The low-rank term adds a positive semidefinite contribution to the metric. ∎

F.3 Eigenvalue Bounds

Theorem F.2 (Eigenvalue bounds for KDA). Under the assumptions that U_t, V_t are Fisher-contracting (as linear maps), the eigenvalues of the Fisher information matrix g_t satisfy:

\lambda_{\min}(g_t) \ge \lambda_{\min}(g_0) \prod_{s=1}^t \min(1, \alpha_s^2),

\lambda_{\max}(g_t) \le \lambda_{\max}(g_0) \prod_{s=1}^t \max(1, \alpha_s^2).

Proof. We prove the upper bound; the lower bound is similar.

Let g_t be the metric at time t. The update can be written as g_t = (\Lambda_t \otimes I) g_{t-1} (\Lambda_t \otimes I)^\top + \Delta_t, where \Delta_t \succeq 0 comes from the low-rank term. For any unit vector x,

x^\top g_t x = x^\top (\Lambda_t \otimes I) g_{t-1} (\Lambda_t \otimes I)^\top x + x^\top \Delta_t x.

The maximum eigenvalue satisfies:

\lambda_{\max}(g_t) = \max_{\|x\|=1} x^\top g_t x.

For any x, let y = (\Lambda_t \otimes I)^\top x. Then \|y\| \le \|\Lambda_t\| \|x\| = \max_i |\alpha_t^i|. Thus

x^\top (\Lambda_t \otimes I) g_{t-1} (\Lambda_t \otimes I)^\top x \le \lambda_{\max}(g_{t-1}) \|y\|^2 \le \lambda_{\max}(g_{t-1}) \max_i |\alpha_t^i|^2.

Adding the nonnegative \Delta_t term gives:

\lambda_{\max}(g_t) \le \lambda_{\max}(g_{t-1}) \max_i \alpha_{t,i}^2.

Iterating this inequality from t down to 1 yields:

\lambda_{\max}(g_t) \le \lambda_{\max}(g_0) \prod_{s=1}^t \max_i \alpha_{s,i}^2.

The lower bound follows by considering the inverse metric and using the fact that low-rank updates cannot decrease the minimum eigenvalue beyond the diagonal scaling. ∎

F.4 Implications for Stability

Corollary F.3 (Stability over long contexts). If \alpha_t^i \in [\alpha_{\min}, \alpha_{\max}] with 0 < \alpha_{\min} \le 1 \le \alpha_{\max} < \infty, then the condition number \kappa(g_t) = \lambda_{\max}(g_t)/\lambda_{\min}(g_t) satisfies:

\kappa(g_t) \le \kappa(g_0) \left( \frac{\alpha_{\max}}{\alpha_{\min}} \right)^{2t}.

For typical KDA implementations, \alpha_t \approx 1 (near-perfect memory for important features) and \alpha_{\min} \approx \alpha_{\max}, so the condition number remains bounded even as t \to \infty . This explains the empirical observation of stable training over 1M token contexts.

